  "texts": [
    "We identify a lack of such epistemic infrastructure as a source of epistemic injustice.",
    "This kind of structural dysfunction can give rise to epistemic injustice, we argue, because it (i) impairs the exercise of our distinctly epistemic capacity for enquiry; and (ii) via this impairment constitutes a harm that disproportionately affects marginalised groups.",
    "Algorithmic systems have far reaching effects and can be implicated in epistemic injustice.",
    "This has also been discussed by various authors, who highlight relationships between new digital technologies and cases of epistemic injustice.",
    "Origgi and Ciranna (2017) discuss the risk of our online personas creating a \"representational crisis\" (p.309) in users if there is a dissonance between these online personas and how individuals perceive themselves and their experiences offline."
  ],
